Summary: Predicting customer revenue with Google Analytics data¶

The data come from a Kaggle competition. The objective is to predict the transaction revenue per customer, given a set of indicators from the GStore. In this notebook,

  1. I first check and transform the data to gather all the necessary predictors.
  2. Then, I do extensive exploratory data analyses that involves data visualization with matplotlib, seaborn and plotly.

  3. Since less than 2% of all visitors decided to purchase, the sample is highly imbalanced. Thus, in order to predict the revenue per customer, I carry out a 2-step procedure:

    • First, try to classify buyers vs. non-buyers. Non-buyers obviously will give 0 revenue. Here, I compare the classifying accuracy scores with and without randomly under-sampling to balance out the training sample.

    • Second, given the sample of only the actual buyers, using regression models to predict the revenues.

      For both classification and regression, I will compare the performances of the models: Support Vector Machine, Logistic/Linear Regression, Decision Tree, Random Forest, AdaBoost with Decision Tree, Adaboost with Random Forest, Extreme Gradient Boosting library XGBoost, and Neural Networks.

In the end, XGBoost gives the best performances both in classification and in regression.

  1. Data preparation
  2. Exploratory data analysis
  3. Classification and regression models
    • Classification models, including Classification with under-sampling
    • Regression models, including Hyperparameter tuning for the Neural Network model

def PiePlot_Cat(df, var, target, top):
    fig=make_subplots(rows=1, cols=3, specs=[[{'type':'pie'},{'type':'pie'},{'type':'pie'}]],\
                     subplot_titles=['Visitors with zero '+target,'Visitors with positive '+target,'All visitors'])
    
    count=df[df[target].isna()][var].value_counts().sort_values(ascending=False).reset_index()
    count['index'][top:]='Others'
    fig.add_trace(go.Pie(labels=count['index'], values=count[var],\
                           textposition='inside'), row=1, col=1)
    
    count=df[~df[target].isna()][var].value_counts().sort_values(ascending=False).reset_index()
    count['index'][top:]='Others'
    fig.add_trace(go.Pie(labels=count['index'], values=count[var], \
                           textposition='inside'), row=1, col=2)
    
    count=df[var].value_counts().sort_values(ascending=False).reset_index()
    count['index'][top:]='Others'
    fig.add_trace(go.Pie(labels=count['index'], values=count[var], \
                           textposition='inside'), row=1, col=3)
    for i in fig['layout']['annotations']:
        i['font']['size']=12
        i['y']=0.85
    fig.update_layout(font=dict(size=12), legend_orientation='h', legend=dict(y=0.1), margin=dict(l=0, r=0, t=0, b=20)).show(renderer='png')
     
def BarPlot_Cat(df, var, target, top):
    fig=make_subplots(rows=1, cols=2, specs=[[{'type':'bar'},{'type':'bar'}]],\
                     subplot_titles=['Total '+target+' by top '+var,\
                                     'Conversion rate (positive '+target+')'+'<br>by '+var+' with most visitors'])
    total=df[target].groupby(df[var]).sum(skipna=True).sort_values(ascending=False).to_frame().reset_index()
    fig.append_trace({'x':total[:top][var], 'y':total[:top][target], 'type':'bar'}, 1,1)
    count=df[df[target].notna()][var].value_counts()
    purchased=(count/df[var].value_counts()).sort_values(ascending=False)
    fig.append_trace({'x':count.index[:top], 'y':purchased.loc[count.index[:top]].values, 'type':'bar'}, 1,2)
    fig.update_layout(height=350, showlegend=False, margin=dict(l=20, r=20, t=50, b=50)).show(renderer='png')
    
    subfig=make_subplots(specs=[[{"secondary_y":True}]])
    average=df[target].groupby(df[var]).mean().sort_values(ascending=False)
    subfig.add_trace(go.Bar(x=count.index[:top], y=average.loc[count.index[:top]].values,\
                         name='Average '+target+' per visitor'), secondary_y=False)
    subfig.add_trace(go.Scatter(x=count.index[:top], y=count.values[:top],\
                             name='Number of visitors with positive '+target), secondary_y=True)
    subfig.update_layout(title_text='Average '+target+' per visitor <br> by '+var+' with most visitors', legend=dict(x=1))    
    subfig.update_layout(font=dict(size=12), height=300, margin=dict(l=20, r=20, t=50, b=20)).show(renderer='png')
    
def KDE_Plot(df, var, target, top):
    topvar=df.groupby(var)[target].sum().sort_values(ascending=False).index[:top]
    df=df[(df[target].notna()) & (df[var].isin(topvar.values))]
    plt.figure(figsize=(10,5))
    for i in df[var].unique():
        sns.kdeplot(df[df[var]==i][target].apply(np.log), label=str(i), shade=True)
    plt.title('Density of {} by {} with most visitors'.format(target, var))
    plt.legend()
    plt.show()

In [13]:
def features_plot(ax, mod, l_names, title):
    if 'feature_importances_' in mod.__dir__():
        feature_weights=pd.Series(mod.feature_importances_, index=l_names).sort_values(ascending=False)
    else:
        feature_weights=pd.Series(mod.coef_[0], index=l_names).sort_values(ascending=False)
    sns.barplot(ax=ax, x=feature_weights.values, y=feature_weights.index).set_title(title)

Plotting ROC curves¶

In [22]:
def ROC_plot(classifier, cv, X, y, graph_title, ax):
    for i, (train, test) in enumerate(cv.split(X, y)):
        classifier.fit(X[train], y[train])
        plot_roc_curve(classifier, X[test], y[test],
                             name='ROC fold {}'.format(i),
                             alpha=0.5, lw=1, ax=ax)
    
    ax.plot([0, 1], [0, 1], linestyle='--', lw=2, color='r',
            label='Chance', alpha=.8)
    
    ax.set(xlim=[-0.05, 1.05], ylim=[-0.05, 1.05],
           title="Receiver operating characteristic {}".format(graph_title))
    ax.legend(loc="lower right")
    
cv = StratifiedKFold(n_splits=5)

fig, ax=plt.subplots(4,2,figsize=(10,24))
for i, mod in enumerate(models.keys()):
    ROC_plot(models[mod], cv, X, y, mod, ax[i//2,i%2])
fig.show()

Recall scores: Buyers vs. Non-buyers¶

The sample is highly imbalanced: Most are non-buyers. The fitted models will be biased toward the non-buyer class, giving low recall scores in the case of buyers.

In [23]:
def scores_plot(models, X, y, title, ax):
    scores=[accuracy_score(y, models[mod].predict(X)) for mod in models.keys()]
    sns.barplot(ax=ax, y=scores, x=list(models.keys())).set_title(title)
    print(title,scores)

X_pos=X_test[y_test>0,:]
y_pos=y_test[y_test>0]
X_neg=X_test[y_test==0,:]
y_neg=y_test[y_test==0]

fig, ax=plt.subplots(1,2,figsize=(12,5))
scores_plot(models, X_pos, y_pos, 'Recall scores: Buyers', ax[0])
scores_plot(models, X_neg, y_neg, 'Recall scores: Non-buyers', ax[1])

Improve the classification performances by re-balancing the train sample with RandomUnderSampler¶

In [24]:
models=dict({'SVM':SGDClassifier(loss='hinge', max_iter=1000, tol=1e-3),\
            'Logit':SGDClassifier(loss='log', max_iter=1000, tol=1e-3),\
            'DT':DecisionTreeClassifier(),\
            'RF':RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators=3),\
            'DT_Ada':AdaBoostClassifier(DecisionTreeClassifier(max_depth=5)),\
            'RF_Ada':AdaBoostClassifier(RandomForestClassifier(max_depth=5,n_estimators=3)),\
            'XGB':xgb.XGBClassifier(n_estimators=100),\
            'NN':MLPClassifier()})

scores_positive=pd.DataFrame(index=range(5), columns=models.keys())
scores_negative=pd.DataFrame(index=range(5), columns=models.keys())

kfold=StratifiedKFold(n_splits=5)
j=0
for i_train, i_test in kfold.split(X,y):
    X_train, y_train = RandomUnderSampler('majority').fit_resample(X[i_train,:], y[i_train])
    X_test, y_test = X[i_test,:], y[i_test]
    
    for mod in models.keys():
        models[mod].fit(X_train, y_train)
    
    X_pos=X_test[y_test>0,:]
    y_pos=y_test[y_test>0]
    X_neg=X_test[y_test==0,:]
    y_neg=y_test[y_test==0]
    
    scores_positive.loc[j]=[accuracy_score(y_pos, models[mod].predict(X_pos)) for mod in models.keys()]
    scores_negative.loc[j]=[accuracy_score(y_neg, models[mod].predict(X_neg)) for mod in models.keys()]
    j+=1

fig=plt.figure(figsize=(12,4))
fig.add_subplot(1,2,1)
plt.errorbar(x=scores_positive.columns.values, y=scores_positive.mean(), yerr=scores_positive.std(), fmt='o')
fig.add_subplot(1,2,2)
plt.errorbar(x=scores_negative.columns.values, y=scores_negative.mean(), yerr=scores_negative.std(), fmt='o')
fig.axes[0].set_title('Recall scores: Buyers')
fig.axes[1].set_title('Recall scores: Non-buyers')
fig.show()

Hyperparameter tuning for the neural-network model MLPRegressor¶

With the default parameters, MLPRegressor performs quite poorly. After tuning, we see an improvement in the test scores with a different combination of parameters. However, XGBoost still outperforms the tuned MLPRegressor.

In [27]:
from sklearn.model_selection import GridSearchCV

params={'activation':['relu','tanh'],\
       'solver':['lbfgs', 'sgd', 'adam'],\
        'learning_rate':['constant','adaptive'],\
       'alpha':[0.01,0.001,0.0001]}

clf=GridSearchCV(MLPRegressor(), params, cv=5, scoring='neg_mean_squared_error')
clf.fit(X, y)
